<paragraph blockId="3.[151,764,654,681]" box="[151,764,654,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,764,654,681]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="443" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="(Han &amp; Cui, 1991)" baseAuthorityName="Han &amp; Cui" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[151,764,654,681]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Neohydatothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="443" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xestosternitus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,764,654,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,525,654,681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">Neohydatothrips xestosternitus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Han Y. F. &amp; Cui Y. Q." box="[541,756,654,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="443" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref2492" refString="Han Y. F. &amp; Cui Y. Q. (1991) Three new species of Thysanoptera (Insecta) from the Hengduan Mountains, China. Entomotaxonomia, 13 (1), 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="1991">Han &amp; Cui, 1991</bibRefCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,727,1041]" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">
This sericothripinae species was originally described from 
<collectingCountry box="[809,879,727,753]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">China</collectingCountry>
, and is here recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1183,1241,727,753]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">India</collectingCountry>
for the first time. The species can be recognized by the dark brown body with abdominal segments V–VI yellow (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1287,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[175,1409,191,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[165,1421,179,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. (1) Psephenothrips uttarakhandensis sp. n. Female; (2) Neohydatothrips xestosternitus, Female. Psephenothrips uttarakhandensis, Female, 3–7: (3) Head and pronotum; (4) Tergites IX–X; (5) Prosternum; (6) Pelta; (7) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781867" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781867/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="443">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); legs yellow at extreme bases of fore tibae and apices of femora, all tarsi yellow. Antennal segments II–III yellow, II brown on basal third. Fore wing paler on apical half with a subbasal band. Head with polygonal reticulation. Pronotum polygonally reticulate; blotch area small with transverse anastomosing striae. Mesonotum with transverse anastomosing striae and metanotum with longitudinal anastomosing striae. Abdomen with rows of microtrichia, absent on IX and X. Tergite VIII with a complete comb of microtrichia posteromarginally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
